#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:10
msgid "4.3 Beyond Single Layers: Stacking for Deep Learning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:12
msgid ""
"The Restricted Boltzmann Machine, as presented in Section [4.2 Restricted"
" Boltzmann Machine (RBM)](/kpp-theoretical-foundations\\kpp-theoretical-"
"foundations-bm-restricted), is a powerful generative model with a single "
"layer of latent variables. However, many real-world datasets, i.e. "
"images, speech, natural language, exhibit <b>hierarchical structure</b>. "
"Low-level features (edges, phonemes, word fragments) combine to form mid-"
"level features (shapes, syllables, phrases), which in turn combine to "
"form high-level concepts (objects, words, semantics). A single-layer "
"latent variable model, no matter how many hidden units it possesses, may "
"struggle to capture such multi-level abstractions efficiently. This "
"limitation motivates the <b>stacking</b> of RBMs to form <b>Deep Belief "
"Networks (DBNs)</b> and <b>Deep Boltzmann Machines (DBMs)</b> . Stacking "
"transforms a shallow generative model into a deep, hierarchical one, "
"capable of learning progressively more abstract representations of the "
"data. This section describes the greedy layer-wise training procedure "
"that made deep generative models practical, and explains how stacked RBMs"
" connect to the broader landscape of deep learning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:15
msgid "<b>The Motivation: Hierarchical Feature Learning</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:17
msgid ""
"Consider the task of modeling a collection of face images. A shallow RBM "
"with a single hidden layer might learn localized Gabor-like edge "
"detectors as its hidden features. These are useful, but they fail to "
"capture the higher-order regularities of faces: the spatial arrangement "
"of eyes, nose, and mouth, or the characteristic symmetries of facial "
"structure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:19
msgid ""
"A deep architecture, by contrast, can learn a <b>hierarchy of "
"representations</b>:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:21
msgid ""
"<b>First hidden layer</b>: Detects low-level features such as oriented "
"edges and corners."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:22
msgid ""
"<b>Second hidden layer</b>: Combines edges to form mid-level features "
"like facial parts (eye, nose, mouth detectors)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:23
msgid ""
"<b>Third hidden layer</b>: Combines facial parts to form high-level, "
"abstract representations of whole faces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:25
msgid ""
"This hierarchical composition mirrors the structure of the visual cortex "
"and enables the model to represent complex data distributions with "
"exponentially fewer parameters than a shallow model of comparable "
"representational power."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:27
msgid "<b>Deep Belief Networks: Composition of RBMs</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:29
msgid ""
"A <b>Deep Belief Network (DBN)</b> is a generative model composed of "
"multiple layers of stochastic, latent variables. The top two layers form "
"an <b>undirected</b> RBM, while the lower layers form a <b>directed</b> "
"sigmoid belief network. Specifically, a DBN with $L$ hidden layers is "
"defined as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:31
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The top two layers, $\\mathbf{h}^{(L-1)}$ and $\\mathbf{h}^{(L)}$, form "
"an RBM."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:32
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The remaining layers are connected via directed, top-down generative "
"weights: $\\mathbf{h}^{(l)}$ generates $\\mathbf{h}^{(l-1)}$ for $l = "
"L-1, \\ldots, 1$, with $\\mathbf{h}^{(0)} = \\mathbf{v}$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:34
msgid "The joint distribution factorizes as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:36
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"P(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h}^{(1)}, \\ldots, \\mathbf{h}^{(L)}) = "
"P(\\mathbf{h}^{(L-1)}, \\mathbf{h}^{(L)}) \\prod_{l=1}^{L-2} "
"P(\\mathbf{h}^{(l)} \\mid \\mathbf{h}^{(l+1)})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:38
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"where $P(\\mathbf{h}^{(L-1)}, \\mathbf{h}^{(L)})$ is the RBM distribution"
" at the top, and the conditional distributions $P(\\mathbf{h}^{(l)} \\mid"
" \\mathbf{h}^{(l+1)})$ are those of a sigmoid belief network."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:40
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The directed connections enable efficient <b>ancestral sampling</b>: to "
"generate a sample, one first samples from the top RBM to obtain "
"$\\mathbf{h}^{(L-1)}$ and $\\mathbf{h}^{(L)}$, then propagates downward "
"through the directed layers, sampling each layer in turn."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:42
msgid "<b>Greedy Layer-Wise Training</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:44
msgid ""
"Training a deep generative model with many layers of latent variables is "
"challenging due to the <b>explaining-away</b> effect and the "
"intractability of exact inference. The breakthrough that made DBNs "
"practical was <b>greedy layer-wise pre-training</b>, introduced by "
"Hinton, Osindero, and Teh in 2006."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:46
msgid ""
"The core idea is elegantly simple: <b>train one RBM at a time, and stack "
"them</b>."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:48
msgid "<b>Algorithm: Greedy Layer-Wise Training of a DBN</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:50
msgid "<b>Train the first RBM</b>:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:51
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Treat the visible data $\\mathbf{v}$ as the visible layer and introduce a"
" hidden layer $\\mathbf{h}^{(1)}$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:52
msgid "Train an RBM on the data using contrastive divergence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:53
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"After training, the RBM defines a generative model $P(\\mathbf{v}, "
"\\mathbf{h}^{(1)})$ and an inference model $P(\\mathbf{h}^{(1)} \\mid "
"\\mathbf{v})$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:55
msgid "<b>Generate training data for the next layer</b>:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:56
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Use the trained inference model to compute the posterior probabilities "
"$P(\\mathbf{h}^{(1)} \\mid \\mathbf{v})$ for each training example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:57
msgid ""
"These posterior probabilities (or samples from them) become the \"data\" "
"for training the next RBM. They represent the data in the feature space "
"learned by the first hidden layer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:59
msgid "<b>Train the second RBM</b>:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:60
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Treat the vectors $\\mathbf{h}^{(1)}$ as visible units and introduce a "
"second hidden layer $\\mathbf{h}^{(2)}$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:61
msgid "Train an RBM on these feature vectors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:63
msgid "<b>Repeat</b> for as many layers as desired."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:65
msgid ""
"After this unsupervised pre-training, the stacked RBMs can be converted "
"into a DBN by discarding the bottom-up recognition weights of all but the"
" first layer, and using the top-down generative weights to define the "
"directed model. Alternatively, weights can be used to initialize a deep "
"neural network for <b>discriminative fine-tuning</b> using "
"backpropagation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:67
msgid "<b>Why Greedy Layer-Wise Training Works</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:69
msgid ""
"The effectiveness of greedy layer-wise training can be understood from "
"several perspectives:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:71
msgid ""
"<b>Variational Lower Bound</b>: Adding a new hidden layer and training it"
" as an RBM on the inferred features of the previous layer can be shown to"
" improve a variational lower bound on the log-likelihood of the data "
"under the expanded model. Each additional layer tightens the bond."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:72
msgid ""
"<b>Feature Abstraction</b>: Each RBM learns to model the distribution of "
"features produced by the layer below. Since these features are already "
"somewhat abstract and decorrelated, the next RBM can focus on capturing "
"higher-order dependencies among them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:73
msgid ""
"<b>Avoiding Local Minima</b>: Deep supervised networks trained from "
"random initializations often get stuck in poor local minima due to the "
"complex, non-convex loss landscape. Pre-training initializes the weights "
"in a region of parameter space that corresponds to a sensible generative "
"model of the data, providing a far better starting point for subsequent "
"discriminative fine-tuning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:75
msgid "<b>Deep Boltzmann Machines (DBMs)</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:77
msgid ""
"A closely related architecture is the <b>Deep Boltzmann Machine (DBM)</b>"
" , introduced by Salakhutdinov and Hinton in 2009. Unlike a DBN, where "
"only the top two layers form an undirected RBM, a DBM is a <b>fully "
"undirected </b>model with multiple hidden layers. All connections are "
"symmetric, and there are no directed edges."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:79
msgid "The energy function for a DBM with two hidden layers is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:81
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"E(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h}^{(1)}, \\mathbf{h}^{(2)}) = -\\mathbf{v}^\\top"
" \\mathbf{W}^{(1)} \\mathbf{h}^{(1)} - (\\mathbf{h}^{(1)})^\\top "
"\\mathbf{W}^{(2)} \\mathbf{h}^{(2)} - \\mathbf{b}^\\top \\mathbf{v} - "
"(\\mathbf{c}^{(1)})^\\top \\mathbf{h}^{(1)} - (\\mathbf{c}^{(2)})^\\top "
"\\mathbf{h}^{(2)}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:83
msgid ""
"DBMs retain the full undirected nature of the Boltzmann machine, which "
"makes them more principled probabilistic models than DBNs. However, exact"
" inference is even more challenging, and training typically requires a "
"more sophisticated procedure, often involving mean-field approximations "
"or persistent contrastive divergence with carefully designed "
"initialization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:85
msgid ""
"In practice, DBNs have been more widely adopted due to their simpler "
"training procedure and direct compatibility with feedforward neural "
"network initialization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:87
msgid "<b>From Unsupervised Pre-Training to Discriminative Fine-Tuning</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:89
msgid ""
"One of the most impactful applications of stacked RBMs was "
"<b>unsupervised pre-training for deep supervised learning</b>. Before the"
" widespread adoption of techniques like batch normalization, ReLU "
"activations, and large labeled datasets (e.g., ImageNet), training deep "
"neural networks with many hidden layers was notoriously difficult. "
"Gradients would vanish or explode, and optimization would stall in poor "
"local minima."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:91
msgid "The RBM pre-training pipeline provided a solution:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:93
msgid ""
"<b>Pre-train</b> a stack of RBMs in an unsupervised manner on unlabeled "
"data (which was often abundant)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:94
msgid ""
"<b>Unroll</b> the stacked RBMs to form a deep feedforward network with "
"the same weights. This network effectively implements the bottom-up "
"inference pathway."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:95
msgid "<b>Add a classification layer</b> on top of the highest-level features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:96
msgid ""
"<b>Fine-tune</b> the entire network using backpropagation on the labeled "
"data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:98
msgid ""
"This approach achieved state-of-the-art results on MNIST and, more "
"impressively, enabled the first significant reduction in error rates on "
"the TIMIT speech recognition benchmark. It demonstrated that deep "
"architectures could be trained effectively if initialized properly, "
"paving the way for the deep learning revolution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:100
msgid "<b>The End of the Pre-Training Era and the Legacy of Stacked RBMs</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:102
msgid ""
"By the early 2010s, advances in optimization (momentum, RMSprop, Adam), "
"activation functions (ReLU and variants), regularization (dropout), and "
"the availability of massive labeled datasets made unsupervised pre-"
"training less necessary for many supervised tasks. End-to-end supervised "
"training of deep networks from random initialization became the norm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:104
msgid "However, the conceptual legacy of stacked RBMs endures:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:106
msgid ""
"They established the <b>viability of deep architectures</b> and the "
"importance of <b>hierarchical feature learning</b>."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:107
msgid ""
"They demonstrated the value of <b>unsupervised representation "
"learning</b> as a precursor to supervised tasks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:108
msgid ""
"They introduced <b>contrastive divergence</b> and <b>greedy layer-wise "
"training</b>, which remain valuable tools in the generative modeling "
"toolkit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:109
msgid ""
"They inspired subsequent generative models, including <b>Variational "
"Autoencoders (VAEs)</b> and <b>Generative Adversarial Networks "
"(GANs)</b>, which also learn hierarchical latent representations, albeit "
"with different training objectives."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:111
msgid ""
"Moreover, in domains where labeled data is scarce but unlabeled data is "
"plentiful, unsupervised pre-training with RBMs or their modern "
"descendants (e.g., deep belief networks, deep Boltzmann machines) remains"
" a relevant and effective strategy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:113
msgid "<b>Stacking Beyond RBMs: The General Principle</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:115
msgid ""
"The principle of stacking simple modules to build deep, hierarchical "
"models extends far beyond RBMs. Modern deep learning is built on this "
"exact idea:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:117
msgid ""
"<b>Convolutional neural networks</b> stack convolutional layers to learn "
"increasingly complex visual features."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:118
msgid ""
"<b>Transformers</b> stack self-attention layers to capture hierarchical "
"linguistic structure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:119
msgid ""
"<b>Diffusion models</b> stack denoising steps to gradually refine "
"generated samples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:121
msgid ""
"The RBM stack was the first practical demonstration that <b>greedy layer-"
"wise construction</b> could bootstrap the training of deep generative "
"models. This insight remains a cornerstone of deep learning methodology."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:123
msgid "<b>Summary</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:125
msgid ""
"<b>Stacking RBMs</b> forms <b>Deep Belief Networks (DBNs)</b> and <b>Deep"
" Boltzmann Machines (DBMs)</b> , enabling hierarchical feature learning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:126
msgid ""
"<b>Greedy layer-wise training</b> trains one RBM at a time, using the "
"inferred features of one layer as data for the next."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:127
msgid ""
"DBNs combine an undirected top RBM with directed lower layers, while DBMs"
" are fully undirected.- Pre-trained stacks of RBMs provided effective "
"<b>weight initializations</b> for deep supervised networks, fueling early"
" deep learning successes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:128
msgid ""
"Although largely supplanted by end-to-end supervised training on large "
"datasets, stacked RBMs remain historically significant and practically "
"useful in label-scarce regimes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-bm-deep.md:129
msgid ""
"The concept of <b>hierarchical representation learning</b> pioneered by "
"stacked RBMs is foundational to modern deep learning architectures."
msgstr ""

